Assistant: Five books recommended by critics, readers, or both include:
•	H is for Hawk by Helen Macdonald (2015) – This memoir reflects on the author’s loss of her father, sparking her to train her own goshawk in its wake. It beautifully integrates reflections on love, the nature of life, and nature itself.
•	The Unlikely Pilgrimage of Harold Fry by Rachel Joyce (2012) – A novel about a man who goes to send a letter and decides to just keep walking instead to deliver it on foot. A story about love and relationships and the things we carry deep inside of us.
•	How to Build a Girl by Caitlin Coran (2014) – This book tells the story of Johannah, a young woman trying to escape her background while she finds a career, a sense of self, and her sexuality. Set in England, this book is cited as “insightful, heartwarming, and very entertaining” by Penguin publishing house.
•	Untamed by Glennon Doyle (2020) – Part memoir, part inspirational self-help, this book has been widely hailed. Many have praised the author and book for its honesty, humor, and wisdom.
•	Sensational: The Hidden History of America’s “Girl Stunt Reporters” by Kim Todd (2021) – The late 1800s saw journalism changing and young women going into the field and undercover to expose corruption and degradation in various areas. But then there was a backlash and the term ‘stunt reporter’ developed negative connotations, though their style would go on to change reporting and non-fiction writing for the better.


