Assistant: Cheng I Sao

In the annals of history, few raiders have left a more profound impact than Cheng I Sao. Her journey began in a Chinese brothel, where she worked as a prostitute. However, fate had grander plans for her. In 1801, she married Cheng I, a formidable corsair, and together they forged one of China's most powerful pirate armies. Their fleet consisted of hundreds of ships and boasted a staggering 50,000 men. With audacity, they pillaged fishing vessels, supply junks, and coastal villages in Southern China.

Tragedy struck when Cheng I met his demise in 1807. Seizing the opportunity, Mrs. Cheng maneuvered her way into power and formed an alliance with Chang Pao, a trusted lieutenant, and lover. The duo embarked on a spree of plunder across Southeast Asia, amassing a fleet that rivaled the navies of many nations. Not content with mere piracy, Mrs. Cheng established a strict code of conduct for her pirates. Any violation, such as the rape of female prisoners, warranted beheading, while deserters faced the punishment of having their ears severed.

Her brutal reign earned Mrs. Cheng the title of public enemy number one in the eyes of the Chinese government. In 1810, the British and Portuguese navies were enlisted to capture her and bring her to justice. Rather than engage in a treacherous sea battle, Mrs. Cheng displayed her cunning. She negotiated the surrender of her fleet and relinquished her cutlass in exchange for the preservation of her ill-gotten riches. Retiring as one of history's most triumphant pirates, she later ran a gambling house until her death in 1844 at the age of 69.

