tinker_cookbook.supervised.train:259 [[92mINFO[0m] <|begin_of_text|>User: Pretend that you are a high-school student preparing to graduate. And then write a short story about a baby duck who isn’t ready to be on its own. Give it a positive spin at the end to show the high-schooler is actually excited about leaving.

Assistant: There once was a duckling who lived in a beautiful pond with her mom, dad, and six brothers and sisters. Ever since she was born, she would swim in a row with her siblings behind her mom as they explored the pond, played, and found food. They even slept all together in the corner by the reeds. 

Then one day, the duckling’s mom pulled her aside and said, “Little One, it’s time for you to leave and explore the pond on your own.” The duckling was incredibly confused; leaving her family? Where would she go? What would she do? Where would she sleep if she didn’t sleep in the reeds? 

The duckling swam away quietly, completely unsure of what she was supposed to do now. She was so upset that she left the pond and started walking across the green grass, lost in her own thoughts. 

Finally, she stumbled upon another pond - one she had never seen before. A whole group of young ducks came swimming over and shouting at her, “what are you doing here? Where did you come from?”

While the young duck was scared, she explained how she had left home to find a new home. Within a few minutes, all the other ducks were telling their stories about when they left home and how fun it was to be out on your own. She didn’t feel so alone anymore; in fact, she was pretty excited.

