tinker_cookbook.supervised.train:259 [[92mINFO[0m] <|begin_of_text|>User: Help me beat writer’s block! Give me a few tips on how to overcome the mental wall that keeps me from writing something awesome.

Assistant: Writer’s block can affect anyone, from hopeful college essayists to elementary book reporters and award-winning novelists. Many creative minds chalk it up to burnout but knowing the cause doesn’t always provide the solution to get you in a clear mindset to write again. 

Read on for a few tips on how to overcome writer’s block and get back to a place of creative prowess. 

•	Seek inspiration from another writer. 

Read for fun and inspiration! Delve into a book to read the words of one of your favorite authors. Sometimes their creativity can rub off on you! 

•	Write about your feelings, your day, your family… anything to get your creativity headed in the right direction. 

Renowned poet Charles Bukowski once said, “writing about writer’s block is better than not writing at all.” As long as you are actively writing whatever comes to mind, you are making strides toward inspiration to write something brilliant. 

•	Take a step back and take care of yourself. 

Sometimes writers push themselves too hard, too far, to come up with something well-written before a deadline, either self-imposed or professional. Step back and take care of yourself in other ways to clear your mind and feel refreshed. Take a bubble bath, spend time with friends and loved ones, binge a television show… do things that make you happy without the written word. Then come back to it rejuvenated. 

•	Find a creative writing prompt that restores the thrill and fun of writing! 

“Pretend that you are an alien from another planet and you’ve just seen a cow for the first time. What are your thoughts?” 

Writing prompts can be silly, fun, and great ways to jumpstart your creativity. You don’t have to take yourself too seriously. Simply let your imagination play out on the paper. 

•	Work your brain without words. 

Burnout is a real struggle for writers, and sometimes your brain needs a break from words. This would be a good time to break out a jigsaw puzzle, find fun in numbers with sudoku, or paint a picture. You can aim to strengthen your brain’s creative process while not having to worry about what to write for a while. 

•	Declutter your space to declutter your mind. 

Writer’s block can occur when you feel overwhelmed with the clutter of your home and your long list of things to do. Take the time to clean and organize your space, beginning with your work areas. Clear your to-do list of as much as you can to satisfy your brain’s anxiety over having so much to do. 

•	Schedule a time to “meet” your muse. 

Harness your writing muse by scheduling specific times to write. If creativity strikes outside of those specific times, then great – write. If not, then don’t force yourself to come up with words that you don’t have. Stress puts strain on creativity. 

Hopefully, these suggestions will help you overcome writer’s block, or at least inspire you to come up with methods for getting your creativity back. Good luck!  


