tinker_cookbook.supervised.train:259 [[92mINFO[0m] <|begin_of_text|>User: Which famous American lawyer famously coined the phrase "Jane Crow" concerning restrictive civil liberties?

Assistant: Pauli Murray coined the phrase "Jane Crow." In the 1940s, Murray was the only woman in a class of law students. At the time, the U.S. laws protected segregation by racial background often referred to as Jim Crow laws. Murray took that idea a step further and characterized prejudice against women using the term "Jane Crow." As a law student, Murray wrote a paper on the unconstitutionality of the Supreme Court case of Plessy v. Ferguson. She argued that the case violated the Fourteenth Amendment's Equal Protection Clause. Her argument was so influential that her professor gave her paper to Thurgood Marshall and his team and helped them develop their argument against segregation. Murray not only influenced the career of Marshall but also another U.S. Supreme Court Justice: Ruth Bader Ginsburg. A 2021 documentary about Murray, called "My Name is Pauli Murray," focused on her life and career as a brilliant, queer, Black, gender-nonconforming scholar.

