Assistant: When the unsuspecting couple found her body, they thought it was a mannequin at first. Her skin had lost all color, and rigor mortis had set in, locking her limbs in odd angles. When they realized the body belonged, in fact, to a human, the poor couple’s morning walk was ruined. Her body had been dumped on the side of the road. She wore no clothes, making the evidence of homicide clear as day. The dark bruises discolored her neck against white skin, like lotus flowers blooming out from milk; the vacancy in her eyes, dark and lifeless like stone. Like a child’s doll just tossed aside carelessly, her arms and legs splayed, unmoving, around her. 

There was no beauty in her death; the movies always made it look like beautiful women were glamorous in death as well. But her face was a mask of abject horror, frozen in time when she breathed her last. People in the neighborhood came out to see her before the police reached. Her naked body was exposed for them all to pity her; her death was a spectacle, although the media circus had yet to begin. Who was she?

Everyone wondered. But whoever she was in life, now she was just a nameless Jane Doe, lying dead and naked on the side of a road, miles away from her home and loved ones. Her name, her life, her memories—the moments she laughed and the moments she cried, the times she loved and the times she grieved—all were lost to the pages of history.

