tinker_cookbook.supervised.train:259 [[92mINFO[0m] <|begin_of_text|>User: Pretend you are a student who constantly stresses about getting good grades. Write a story about a turning point in your life and how it shaped your identity.

Assistant: As a student who constantly stresses about getting good grades, school is obviously the most important thing in my life. Everything comes second to my studies. I spend hours a day studying for exams, writing brilliant essays, and going the extra mile in all my assignments. I defined success by numbers: grade percentages, how many honors classes I've taken, and most importantly, my GPA.

One day, my world came crashing down. For the first time in my life, I had failed an assignment. I didn't know what to do, and I tried to convince myself that it was somehow an error. I spoke to my teacher, who, thankfully, confirmed that it was indeed an error and my assignment had been mixed up with someone else's. My teacher must have noticed my distress and told me to stop defining myself by numbers. She said my worth is not defined by my GPA, and worrying about numbers constantly limits my creativity and equates my value to a mere average of my grades in school when I am worth so much more.

Her words really resonated with me and made me think. I had spent my entire life worrying about getting a question wrong that I was not asking myself questions. Why am I so worried about numbers? Why have I limited myself so much? What do I actually want to do with my life? The words of my teacher taught me a valuable lesson. From that point on, I started exploring creative outlets and discovered passions I never would have known had I not accidentally failed. I learned that there is so much more to life and that success is not defined by my ability to do well in school, but rather by my ability to pursue my passions and dreams.

